Title

Spatial and temporal effects on SARS-CoV-2 contamination of the healthcare environment

Abbreviated Title

SARS-CoV-2 Healthcare Contamination

Abstract

Introduction:

Despite infection control measures, transmission of SARS-CoV-2 infection has been observed in the healthcare and hospital settings. In a recent study of SARS-CoV-2-infected and -uninfected patients inadvertently roomed together, 39% of exposed uninfected patients developed COVID-19. Risk of SARS-CoV-2 transmission was associated with source patients who had low cycle threshold (Ct), i.e., high viral load, in their diagnostic testing.1

SARS-CoV-2 transmission can be mediated by droplets, aerosols, or fomites. Prior studies have demonstrated that SARS-CoV-2 extensively contaminates surfaces in the healthcare environment.2 But the spatial extent of contamination and how contamination changes during the course of hospitalization remain less well understood.3

We have previously applied spatial mapping and systematic sampling to define how multidrug-resistant organisms cluster in the hospital environment [site pending ICHE manuscript]. We now extend the methods we have developed to understand how SARS-CoV-2 contamination is distributed spatially, and how it changes over time.

Materials and Methods:

  • Study Design, Setting, and Population: We performed a prospective cohort study at the Hospital of the University of Pennsylvania (HUP), an academic medical center in Philadelphia, PA, USA. (IRB protocol #843273). Patients with COVID-19 were housed on multiple hospital units over the course of the study according to bed availability. All rooms underwent daily cleaning, according to hospital protocol. Environmental services (EVS) staff used disposable disinfectant wipes (quaternary ammonium disinfectant) for use on high-touch objects (one wipe per surface). Floors were cleaned using a microfiber mop and a chlorine-based disinfectant (sodium dichloroisocyanurate).

  • Causal Model: We hypothesized that SARS-CoV-2 contamination would decay with physical distance from patient and with time from COVID-19 diagnosis. We also hypothesized that high-touch objects would be more frequently contaminated with SARS-CoV-2 RNA than low-touch objects.

  • Specimen Collection and SARS-CoV-2 RT-PCR: COVID-19 patient rooms were swabbed longitudinally until day 28 or patient discharge from the hospital (i.e., hospital days 1,2,7,14,21,and 28). Longitudinal sampling continued if the patient was removed from COVID-19 isolation precautions or the patient transferred to a new hospital room. Multiple surfaces were swabbed within each patient room using a Copan FLOQ(TM) swab and a sterile template (20cm2). Specific surfaces are listed in Table 1. Swabs were immediately placed into buffered AVL and frozen prior to further processing. Specimens then underwent RNA extraction and RT-PCR targeting the SARS-CoV-2 N1 region in triplicate.

  • Distance Data Collection: Distance from the environmental sampling site to the patients head of bed was recorded using a laser measuring device (Bosch GLM 20). Templates were affixed to each surface and the linear distance from the patients head of bed to the sample site was measured.

  • Definition of Exposures and Outcomes: Patient rooms were eligible for inclusion in the study if the occupant had a positive test for SARS-CoV-2 within the prior 7 days and was admitted to a new patient room with COVID-19 isolation precautions. The primary study outcome of interest, detection of SARS-CoV-2 by PCR assay, was determined by detection of any quantifiable RNA.

  • Statistical Methods: Data were organized using R statistical software version 3.6.1,4 and plots generated using the ggplot2 package.5 We examined how (1) distance from the patient and (2) time since COVID-19 diagnosis relate to the probability of SARS-CoV-2 detection using a binomial model with a logit link. We also evaluated mixed-effects model incorporating a random effect for subjects to account for clustering of longitudinal data, and to evaluate inter-subject differences. Models were fit using Stan Hamiltonian Monte Carlo (HMC) version 2.21, via the brms package with default, weakly-informative priors.6,7 Prior predictive modeling was performed, and models were fit with 4 chains of 1000 iterations, confirmed with HMC diagnostics (no divergent iterations, Rhat statistic < 1.1 for all parameters, and E-BFMI > 0.2).810 We examined parameter distributions at 50%, 80%, and 95% posterior credible intervals to understand the relationship between exposure and outcome variables.

  • Power and Sample Size: We anticipated that the enrollment of a minumum of 100 subjects would permit detection of a minimum of a 10% decrease probability of surface detection between distance groups with type 1 error less than 0.05.

  • Availability of Data: Data, analysis scripts, and model code are available at https://github.com/bjklab.

Results:

  • Characteristics of subjects hospitalized for COVID-19 during the second (fall 2020) wave: We collected 1334 specimens from 111 unique subject-room pairs, comprising 103 unique subjects (i.e., 7 subjects were transferred at least once during the observation period). The median number of sampling events from each subject-room pair was 1.52 (SD 0.74). Table 1 summarizes the environmental surfaces sampled, whether they were high-touch or low-touch, the proportion of each specimen type from which SARS-CoV-2 RNA was detected by RT-qPCR, and the SARS-CoV-2 copy numbers measured. We did not observe significant differences in copy numbers across the surface types, but the proportion with detectable SARS-CoV-2 did vary widely.

  • SARS-CoV-2 RNA Environmental Contamination Varies with Surface Type But Not Distance from Patient: We evaluated the relationship between the distance from the patients head of the bed and the probability of detecting SARS-CoV-2 on environmental surfaces. There was no significant relationship between distance and the probability of SARS-CoV-2 detection, in contrast to prior studies of MDRO organisms [site ICEMAN ICHE paper], but the suface type was significantly associated with the probability of detection. Floor surfaces had an odds ratio of 67.77 (95% CrI 36.34 to 131.47) of SARS-CoV-2 detection, relative to elevated surfaces. High-touch elevated surfaces had an odds ratio of 7.39 (95% CrI 4.31 to 13.09) of SARS-CoV-2 detection, relative to low-touch elevated surfaces. Figure 1A depicts the results of a multivariable model relating distance from patient, surface location, and whether the surface was high-touch to the probability of SARS-CoV-2 detection.

  • SARS-CoV-2 RNA Environmental Contamination Decays During Prolonged Hospitalization: We evaluated the effect of time from COVID-19 diagnosis on the detection of SARS-CoV-2 RNA in the hospital environment via a multivariable logistic regression model relating time from COVID-19 diagnosis, surface location, and whether the surface was high-touch to the probability of SARS-CoV-2 detection. We found that the probability of detection decreased as time from COVID-19 diagnosis increased, with OR 0.96 (95% CrI 0.94 to 0.98) per day since COVID-19 diagnosis. The most prominent effects were observed on high-touch elevated surfaces and floor surfaces (Figure 1B).

  • SARS-CoV-2 Contamination of the Floor Increases with Pandemic Wave Duration: To understand how subjects differed in the effect of time from COVID-19 diagnosis on SARS-CoV-2 contamination of the hospital environment, we re-fit the above model with the addition of random intercepts and slopes to account for subject-level differences. Figure 2A depicts the best estimate of the effect of time from COVID-19 diagnosis on the contamination in each subjects hospital room. In the figure, the lines representing each subject are colored by when they were enrolled during the course of the local, second-wave COVID-19 case surge. We observed that the contamination of high-touch elevated surfaces did not appear to relate to time from the start of the local case surge. However, contamination of floor surfaces appeared to be greater among subjects enrolled later in the course of the local case surge. To investigate this further, we added an interaction term to the model and found that each day since the start of the start of the local second wave increased the contamination of floor surfaces with OR 1.02 (95% CrI 1.01 to 1.03) (Figure 2B).

  • SARS-CoV-2 Contamination of High-Touch Objects Depends on Subject Characteristics: We found Table 2 .

Discussion:

We sought to define the impact of time and distance on SARS-CoV-2 surface contamination through longitudinal sampling of surfaces within COVID-19 patient rooms. We found that distance from the patients head of bed did not have a significant impact on the probability of detection of SARS-CoV-2 RNA. We had hypothesized that the probability of RNA detection with decrease with distance. However, we found that detection did not vary significantly among any surface group with increased distance. This is likely related to two factors 1) the relatively small size of patient rooms and 2) the physical spread of viral RNA through touch. We observed large differences in the probability of detecting surface contamination by surface type. Floors had high probability of contamination, which did not vary throughout the room. This is likely related to both the role of patient and HCP feet as well as the physical action of mopping which spread body fluids containing viral RNA within the patients room. In contrast, walls had significantly lower probability of contamination. This may be due to the decreased settling of respiratory droplets on vertical surfaces. This finding matches previous description of high probability of floor contamination relative to other surfaces.???

While we did not observe a measurable impact of distance on the probability of surface contamination with SARS-CoV-2 RNA, we did detect a decrease in probability of detection among both high and low-touch surfaces with time from COVID-19 diagnosis. A similar finding was described by Chia et al,??? where patients over 7 days from illness had lower probability of surface contamination within rooms. Interestingly, while the probability of floor contamination decreased with time from diagnosis, the probability remained relatively high at later time points. Combined with the finding that the probability of floor contamination increased with time from the onset of the second COVID-19 Wave, this suggests that external contamination accounts for a significant proportion of floor contamination. Viral RNA carried on the feet of healthcare personnel or the mops of EVS teams may have resulted in increased probability of detection as COVID-19 census increased. Guo et al??? described that floor contamination was discovered in areas where clinical care was not performed, and suggested that it was spread by the feet of HCP.

Our findings are significant as they reveal that varied distances within a patient room have similar probability of surface contamination. This finding supports CDC recommended infection control practices.??? Additionally, our findings highlight the role of touch in surface contamination of patient rooms and the likelihood of extrinsic contamination on SARS-CoV-2 units.

Our study has several limitations. First, our study used quantitative PCR for the detection of SARS-CoV-2 RNA and did not use viral culture to determine the viability from surfaces. Secondly, we did not control for cleaning methods on study units. However, cleaning practices did not undergo significant changes during the study time period and sampling was performed routinely prior to daily cleaning. Finally, while we explored patient characteristics impacted the decay of surface contamination with time and distance, there was limited variability of some measures, making independent associations with viral detection less feasible.

In conclusion, .

Figures:

Figure 1:

Figure 1: Spatial and temporal effects on SARS-CoV-2 RNA contamination in the healthcare environment. (A) Distance from the head of the patients bed is shown on the horizontal axis. The vertical axis depicts the probability of SARS-CoV-2 detection by RT-qPCR according to a logistic regression model incorporating the surface elevation and touch. (B) Days from diagnosis with COVID-19 are shown on the horizontal axis. The vertical axis depicts the probability of SARS-CoV-2 detection by RT-qPCR according to a logistic regression model incorporating the surface elevation and touch. For both plots, the black line shows the best estimate, and shading indicates 50%, 80%, and 95% posterior credible intervals.

Figure 2:

Figure 2: Variation in temporal effects and influence of pandemic duration. (A) Days from diagnosis with COVID-19 are shown on the horizontal axis. The vertical axis depicts the probability of SARS-CoV-2 detection by RT-qPCR according to a logistic regression model incorporating the site elevation and touch, with random subject-level effects. Each line represents the best estimate for a single subjects; lines are colored according to the number of days from the start of the local COVID-19 second case wave. (B) Days from the local start of the second COVID-19 wave are shown on the horizontal axis. The vertical axis depicts the probability of SARS-CoV-2 detection by RT-qPCR according to a logistic regression model incorporating the days from COVID-19 diagnosis, surface elevation, and touch, with an interaction term between the days from the local start of the second COVID-19 wave and the surface type. The black line shows the best estimate, and shading indicates 50%, 80%, and 95% posterior credible intervals.
